'''GLAC''' (pl. ''GLACs'') is an abbreviation for "general ledger accounting code" used primarily by the US military and government agencies for budgetary and inventory purposes, reflecting business transactions, labor costs and income sources across agencies or between facilities. GLACs can also be used to apportion operationing costs and income into separate departments within a single facility. GLACs are represented as by a two character alpha-numerical prefix, specifying department (such as "03" for "private party sales" or "7Q" for "before/after school day care") and followed by a three digit code, specifying the transaction of goods or services within the given department: ie, current assets, receivable goods, fixed assets, liabilities, labor, prepaid supplies, investment revenue, and sources of income. The dual column system of book-keeping generally posts positive, revenue generating GLACs on the righthand column, balancing each out with its contra-account in the lefthand ledger.